  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is there any way to adjust title and font default settings in Google docs?",
  "response": "Yes, you can adjust the title and font default settings in Google Docs to suit your preferences. Here\u2019s how you can do it:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Adjusting the Title Style**\nTo customize the default title style:\n1. Select the title text in your document.\n2. Change the font, size, color, or other formatting options in the toolbar or the \"Format\" menu.\n3. With the title still selected, go to the \"Styles\" dropdown in the toolbar (it usually says \"Normal text\" or \"Title\").\n4. Hover over \"Title\" and click the small arrow next to it.\n5. Select **\"Update 'Title' to match\"**. This will save your custom formatting as the default title style.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Adjusting the Default Font**\nTo change the default font for all new documents:\n1. Open a Google Docs document.\n2. Go to **Format** > **Paragraph styles** > **Normal text** > **Update 'Normal text' to match** (this sets the current font and formatting as the default).\n3. With the same \"Normal text\" dropdown open, select **\"Options\"** > **\"Save as my default styles\"**.\n4. This will apply your chosen font and formatting to all new documents.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Creating Custom Styles**\nIf you want to create a custom style for headings, subheadings, etc.:\n1. Format the text as desired.\n2. Use the \"Styles\" dropdown, hover over the appropriate style (e.g., Heading 1, Heading 2), and click the arrow.\n3. Select **\"Update [style] to match\"** to save your formatting.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Using a Template**\nIf you frequently use specific styles, consider creating a template:\n1. Format a document with your preferred styles.\n2. Go to **File** > **Save as template** (if available) or save it as a template manually by creating a copy in Google Drive.\n\n---\n\nBy following these steps, you can customize the default title and font settings in Google Docs to match your preferences.",
